rationale: Distinct damage mechanism concept describing thermal fatigue, not duplicated by any other entity.
Represents the mechanical loading condition (cyclic stresses), which is conceptually distinct from temperature variations and thermal cycling.
Specifically refers to temperature changes over time, a different concept than cyclic stresses or thermal cycling processes.
Refers to the condition of repeated heating and cooling cycles, which is related to but not identical with cyclic stresses or temperature variations.
Refers specifically to cracking as a damage morphology from thermal fatigue; no conflicting entities to merge with and the name/description are consistent.
Represents a generic metallic component susceptible to damage; distinct concept from the cracking damage morphology, so it should remain separate.
Represents a general mechanical motion phenomenon distinct from differential expansion; both are listed as separate, alternative conditions in the text.
Specifically refers to non-uniform thermal expansion; this is conceptually narrower and distinct from generic relative movement, so it should remain a separate entity.
